WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.400
ask him to ask two questions I want to know. So what do you do? How often do you check MRD?

00:00:06.760 --> 00:00:11.360
And what do you do if the MRD is going up? What was the second question?

00:00:11.500 --> 00:00:18.060
If MRD is rising. So how do you manage that in the context of all the trials you're going to show us?

00:00:19.780 --> 00:00:27.340
So I'm doing MRD testing much more than I expected to be. And it is a very patient driven thing,

00:00:27.340 --> 00:00:34.900
to be honest. Patients are very aware of what MRD means, and they want to know if they've

00:00:34.900 --> 00:00:41.620
achieved MRD negativity. So I kind of can't believe how often we're checking MRD negativity.

00:00:42.700 --> 00:00:50.300
But as we'll talk about, not necessarily outside of studies using it for

00:00:50.300 --> 00:00:57.320
therapy decisions right now. That's my own practice. All right. The second question you

00:00:57.320 --> 00:01:00.800
asked, by the way, I'm just glossing over because that is a very, very difficult question.

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:02.520
That's why I asked it.

00:01:03.260 --> 00:01:14.200
If it's a large slippage, what I usually am doing is I'm bracing patients for the need to switch

00:01:14.200 --> 00:01:18.760
therapy soon, but I'm not necessarily switching right then. I realize that there are colleagues

00:01:18.760 --> 00:01:26.320
here probably on this stage who are initiating therapy when that happens. I know I can name

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:27.300
several, but...

00:01:27.300 --> 00:01:30.940
I guess we'll talk about that in the discussion. So thank you.

00:01:30.940 --> 00:01:34.200
Can you come back for that? I'm not sure. But anyway, all right. So we're going to talk about

00:01:34.200 --> 00:01:41.740
MRD guided therapy for newly diagnosed multiple myeloma. This is a very hard topic. And I'm not

00:01:41.740 --> 00:01:47.140
going to try... I'm not going to give a lot of specific examples of studies where we did it.

00:01:47.220 --> 00:01:52.540
I'm not going to try and explain how the field's been shaped by trials that do this. I want to

00:01:52.540 --> 00:01:57.280
talk about the concept of using it and the pros and cons of using it. Let's start with why it's

00:01:57.280 --> 00:02:01.460
important. Why MRD matters. We obviously know this. We know that MRD refines prognosis beyond

00:02:01.460 --> 00:02:08.240
the usual clinical parameters that we measure, CR and stringent CR. We know that achieving MRD

00:02:08.240 --> 00:02:17.800
negativity correlates with better PFS and overall survival. And it's increasingly being used as a

00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:27.260
surrogate endpoint in newly diagnosed myeloma trials for this reason. This is actually a

00:02:27.260 --> 00:02:27.480
great example of why MRD is so important. And I think it's a great example of why MRD is so important.

00:02:27.480 --> 00:02:27.580
And I think it's a great example of why MRD is so important. And I think it's a great example of why

00:02:27.580 --> 00:02:32.460
complete response rates and complete response rates are so high and survival is so long and

00:02:32.460 --> 00:02:38.700
progression-free survival is so long. We need an earlier marker to keep the field moving forward

00:02:38.700 --> 00:02:47.680
as we refine regimens, right? So this is practical, right? But this is not the same thing as using it

00:02:47.680 --> 00:02:53.320
to make treatment decisions. This is a surrogate endpoint for the outcomes that we care about down

00:02:53.320 --> 00:02:56.500
the road. We just know they're going to happen years later, right?

00:02:57.240 --> 00:03:04.180
I covered this point. We know that this is actually true. This has been shown in transplant

00:03:04.180 --> 00:03:12.140
eligible and ineligible patients, newly diagnosed and in relapsed patients. And we also know that

00:03:12.140 --> 00:03:21.460
there may be some patient subsets where achieving MRD negativity isn't quite as predictive of

00:03:21.460 --> 00:03:27.020
outcome or doesn't overcome certain kinds of risk. The master study, which we've heard about already,

00:03:27.220 --> 00:03:33.060
is an example of an MRD-driven trial where when patients achieve what they called MRD-sure,

00:03:33.200 --> 00:03:39.580
which is basically sustained MRD negativity, they enter a treatment-free observation period.

00:03:40.280 --> 00:03:46.780
And what we saw was that patients who had two or more high-risk cytogenetic features

00:03:46.780 --> 00:03:57.200
basically did more poorly using the strategy. But it may not, you know, it may not be a

00:03:57.200 --> 00:04:02.620
function of having stopped therapy because we also know that in the Griffin study, you have

00:04:02.620 --> 00:04:12.000
very, very similar curves. So again, when you don't have a randomized decision around that MRD

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:17.280
check, there are limitations to what you can learn. I'm going to come back to this point.

00:04:18.280 --> 00:04:27.180
So currently, we know that it's prognostically significant. We talked about it as an eligible

00:04:27.180 --> 00:04:37.580
factor for clinical trials or a surrogate endpoint in clinical trials. And there are selected

00:04:37.580 --> 00:04:45.100
situations where based on some of the data that's emerged that I personally use it. So the main,

00:04:45.240 --> 00:04:50.540
I think the most common scenario is the patient who's on maintenance therapy and sort of suffering

00:04:50.540 --> 00:04:57.160
from years of grade one toxicity that doesn't really necessarily result in an absolute stop

00:04:57.160 --> 00:05:03.080
to therapy, but they just aren't having the quality of life they want. And so they're really

00:05:03.080 --> 00:05:09.080
wanting to get off maintenance therapy. And you're trying to just get as much data as you can

00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:15.220
about, you know, is it rational? Is it safe to do? And knowing that a patient is MRD negative does

00:05:15.220 --> 00:05:20.440
provide maybe some reassurance. And so sometimes I use it that way in a standard risk patient off

00:05:20.440 --> 00:05:25.700
of a study, but that's one of the few examples. The key question is, you know, outside of those

00:05:25.700 --> 00:05:27.080
kinds of isolated scenarios,

00:05:27.140 --> 00:05:32.880
should we be using it to guide management? And so a few things before I sort of like

00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:38.740
render an opinion about that is first, we should be thinking about it as came up earlier as how

00:05:38.740 --> 00:05:43.060
deep is the response? MRD measurements are really how deep have we suppressed disease? Not is it a

00:05:43.060 --> 00:05:47.580
yes, no. We've already learned that there's differences, you know, based on your threshold

00:05:47.580 --> 00:05:53.000
in terms of prognostically what it means to achieve MRD negativity and 10 to the minus fifth

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:57.120
is currently proposed as meaningful for making

00:05:57.120 --> 00:06:02.880
treatment decisions if we're going to study that question. Some people, some studies do use 10 to

00:06:02.880 --> 00:06:10.160
the minus sixth. It's a marrow sampling test right, right now, but there will be blood based MRD

00:06:10.160 --> 00:06:16.640
testing in the future, hopefully. And as we heard in the just the last talk, the biology of

00:06:16.640 --> 00:06:22.640
extramedullary disease is different. And it's important to remember when we're using MRD testing

00:06:22.640 --> 00:06:27.100
to declare somebody, you know, negative, that imaging really doesn't

00:06:27.100 --> 00:06:33.120
need to be part of the equation in these patients. So I'm going to just kind of talk about a couple

00:06:33.120 --> 00:06:41.560
of different basic strategies. One is MRD guided therapy escalation, right? So for example,

00:06:41.620 --> 00:06:45.980
a patient who's MRD positive status post some kind of abduction therapy, we know they have

00:06:45.980 --> 00:06:51.060
inferior outcomes. And so we do something in response to them continuing to be MRD positive.

00:06:51.240 --> 00:06:56.320
We either add consolidation, we switch therapy, we do something like that. This is an example of a

00:06:57.080 --> 00:07:03.320
with Christine Yee at the University of Michigan, where patients started with DRD and then escalated

00:07:03.320 --> 00:07:09.080
to DVRD if they remained MRD positive, and then escalated to the option of transplant if they

00:07:09.080 --> 00:07:13.820
still remained MRD positive. Otherwise, if at some point they become negative, they go on to

00:07:13.820 --> 00:07:18.680
maintenance therapy, right? That was the basic design of the study. And the idea is patients

00:07:18.680 --> 00:07:23.160
loved this study, right? I'm only getting what I need. If I don't need more than a triplet, great.

00:07:23.160 --> 00:07:26.780
The problem, theoretically, right, is that you are,

00:07:27.060 --> 00:07:33.260
potentially selecting for resistant clones before you move in with the full, most intensive,

00:07:33.520 --> 00:07:38.440
most effective regimen, right? So you might be selecting for resistant disease. So this strategy

00:07:38.440 --> 00:07:45.100
too is MRD guided de-escalation, right? So reducing therapeutic intensity or discontinuing therapy if

00:07:45.100 --> 00:07:51.980
a patient becomes MRD negative, biologically a bit more rational. It's actually a refinement of the

00:07:51.980 --> 00:07:56.440
strategy that we already use to treat patients, right? Maintenance therapy, right, is a de-escalation.

00:07:57.040 --> 00:08:04.140
We're using an endpoint, a more powerful endpoint, to decide who gets de-escalation. And numerous

00:08:04.140 --> 00:08:10.900
studies, Master was one. We did another study with Andrei Jakubovic, ELO-KRD, with very, very good

00:08:10.900 --> 00:08:17.700
outcomes. Basically, if patients achieved sustained MRD negativity with ELO-KRD, then they went to an

00:08:17.700 --> 00:08:23.060
ELO-RD maintenance therapy, and we got rid of the carfilzomib and an MRD-driven decision.

00:08:23.060 --> 00:08:27.020
So building it into trials, I just want to, I'm going to kind of leave

00:08:27.020 --> 00:08:33.360
you with just a couple of points. One, most of the data that we actually have looks at it sort

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:40.740
of as a fork in the road. You know, if patients remain positive, we do this, and if patients

00:08:40.740 --> 00:08:46.660
become negative, we do that. That's not really probably best approach. That's not what we learn

00:08:46.660 --> 00:08:51.600
the most from. This is the kind of thing that we learn the most from, where a certain MRD status

00:08:51.600 --> 00:08:55.800
is achieved, and then you compare two different strategies based on the achievement of that

00:08:55.800 --> 00:08:57.000
strategy. We have a certain MRD status, and then you compare two different strategies based on the

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:01.180
achievement of that strategy. We have the lead investigator of a very important study that's

00:09:01.180 --> 00:09:05.580
going to answer the question about, you know, what do we do with MRD-negative patients and

00:09:05.580 --> 00:09:10.560
maintenance therapy and the duration of maintenance, right? So super important trial,

00:09:10.740 --> 00:09:14.120
and I'm going to just leave you with a couple of other examples of well-designed

00:09:14.120 --> 00:09:21.460
key trials that use MRD to guide therapy. We've heard about the MIDAS trial, and, you know,

00:09:21.500 --> 00:09:26.480
we've already learned things because there were randomizations, right? We've already learned that

00:09:26.980 --> 00:09:33.000
transplant doesn't add an awful lot after you achieve MRD-negativity with ISA-KRD induction.

00:09:33.280 --> 00:09:40.320
We've also learned that double transplant doesn't do more than a single transplant in terms of

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:46.400
deepening response if patients are still MRD-positive after induction therapy. But for

00:09:46.400 --> 00:09:51.620
Sergio, we did learn that transplant does sometimes take these MRD-positive patients

00:09:51.620 --> 00:09:56.760
and push them all the way to negative using a 10 to the minus 6 threshold when you add transplant.

00:09:56.960 --> 00:10:00.940
And so I'm going to leave that and just food for thought for future clubs.
